[ ] Refactor and fix all the things that are not working in the Worlds & Map page
    [x] For the World / Places page, I don't really want the two panel / sides separation. I would like to have a full page like the left panel with all the details and information of the place element, and then as a sub-part after the word description and before the place gallery, I want to have a sub-part menu that will be a flex scrolling sub-div that is like the current right side panel.
    [x] When we create a new place, I would like that the app remembers the previous place type selection choice instead of always having the by default `region` type.
    [x] Currently, not everything is easily editable in the left panel in editor mode, we can't rename a place, the place type editor is different (a base text input, whereas in the creation popup menu, it is a drop down choice selection menu, that I prefer, it is easier to not have to write text). I would like to have an easy UI where you can edit each property individually (with layers of beautifuled displayed property / hidden input that swap when editing / saving / canceling). I want subtle edit button (with just a pencil emoji and not much text) next right to each attribute of the place elements.
    [ ] I would like the possibility to move a place higher in the hierarchy as the grand-parent child, or lower in the hierarchy as another sub-place child. And to be practical and not too hard to implement, when we move a place, we unassign all its polygons, and the user will have to manage the polygons assignement.
    [ ] I want the map system to work hierarchially, where we are careful about the current place hierarchy level, but where we can zoom on a selected sub-place if we want to, or go back to parent place level if we want to too. I want the map system to work with areas polygons, that we can associate to a sub-place or not. A sub-place can have multiple polygons linked to it (sometimes, we have to split polygons in two, for instance to create islands, or inner lakes). Under the planet at the continent / oceans / sea levels, I want that each polygon type have a different background color / texture, to separate the water from the earth ground.
    [ ] I think, currently, there are some bugs about the polygons highlighting and also hover detection, and moving points easily breaks things.
    [ ] When we edit the map at a non planet level, but lower in the hierarchy, I want that we are limited to the inside of each areas / polygons, and that we cannot make inner polygons that crosses polygons boundaries, even if it is to go inside another polygon of the same parent place node.
    [ ] I want multiple layers for the map, I don't relly know yet how to organize all that within the current data structures, because I want something very efficient and lightweight to edit at large scale / load / process / view, something that scales well when working on very large maps with a lot of details.
